## 2. CoC Topology: Two Views

### Non-Owner Visibility — My Recommendation

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Non-owners should see a flat access list, NOT the full share tree.**

**Rationale**: In a chain-of-custody system, the sharing topology itself is sensitive metadata. If Alice shares with Bob, and Bob re-shares with Charlie — should Charlie know that Bob was the intermediary? In most enterprise/legal scenarios, **no**. The chain of custody is the *owner's* forensic record.

**What non-owners see**: "This document is shared with: bob, charlie, dave" (flat list, no edges)
**What owners see**: Full tree with who-shared-to-whom edges

This also aligns with TrustFlow's watermarking model — the owner can trace leaks via watermarks, so only they need the topology.

